itects in Ontario. Carr documents a comprehensive selection of Burke's works, including his firm's famous Robert Simpson store in Toronto, the first curtain-wall construction in Canada. She places Burke's life and career within the larger social context, addressing the influence of American architects and architecture, the sociology of professions, the organization of architectural offices, and the history of particular building forms. Toronto Architect Edmund Burke is not only a study of Burke's life and work; it is also an insightful look into the history of Canadian architecture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitectesxBiographiesxCanada. 0aArchitecturexDessins et plansx19e sièclexCanada. 0aArchitecturexDessins et plansx20e sièclexCanada. 0aArchitecturexHistoirex19e sièclexCanada. 0aArchitecturexHistoirex20e sièclexCanada. 0aArchitecture, ModernxHistoryx19th century. 0aArchitecture, Moderny19th centuryxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356486240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564862423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564862/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles